stage. Finally, the Multi-Pseudo-Target supervision significantly increases the 
performance, manifesting its effectiveness in helping training convergence. 
Temporal Consistency Factors: Firstly, we study the factors in the match-
ing problems, including similarity and matching strategies. As shown in Tab. 3, 
both Hungarian and Bidirectional matching show their advantages over the sin-
gle direction matching. Although Hungarian matching can ensure the one-to-one 
matching relationship, it is sensitive to the similarity metric and numerical preci-
sion, both of which are not stable in the early training stage. In contrast, bidirec-
tional matching with the FDE similarity metric nearly achieves the best results 
across all the evaluation metrics. Therefore, we choose bidirectional matching 
with the FDE similarity metric.
